               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18560514-541-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-541-18560514 t18560514-541-offence-1 t18560514-541-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18560514-541-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-541-18560514 t18560514-541-offence-1 t18560514-541-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>541. <persName id="def1-541-18560514" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-541-18560514" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-541-18560514" type="age" value="30"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-541-18560514" type="surname" value="JONES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-541-18560514" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">ELIZABETH JONES</hi>
                  </persName> and <persName id="def2-541-18560514" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-541-18560514" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-541-18560514" type="age" value="33"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-541-18560514" type="surname" value="GRANT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-541-18560514" type="given" value="SUSAN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">SUSAN GRANT</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18560514-541-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18560514-541-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18560514-541-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="pocketpicking"></interp>, stealing 1 purse, value 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; and 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in money; the property of <persName id="t18560514-name-480" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-480" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-480" type="surname" value="TERRY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-480" type="given" value="CHARLES MASTERS"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18560514-541-offence-1 t18560514-name-480"></join>Charles Masters Terry</persName>, from the person of <persName id="t18560514-name-481" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-481" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-481" type="surname" value="TERRY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-481" type="given" value="REBECCA"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18560514-541-offence-1 t18560514-name-481"></join>Rebecca Terry</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. COOPER</hi>. <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-482" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-482" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-482" type="surname" value="TAYLOR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-482" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH TAYLOR</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the driver of a Wellington omnibus from the Elephant and Castle to Shoreditch. On 5th May, about half-past 5 o'clock in the afternoon I was driving from the Elephant and Castle, I was hailed by the two prisoners at Thomas-street in the Borough—I had seen the prisoners before and seen them together—they entered my omnibus, and I made a communication to the conductor—I believe the prisoners left my omnibus in Gracechurch-street—I saw them passing towards Leadenhall-street—the conductor made a communication to me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RIBTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you take up more passengers after the prisoners got in? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; I believe I had ten before them—I only take twelve—believe some one got out at the steps—a lady got in at the statue.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-483" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-483" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-483" type="surname" value="DEAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-483" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY DEAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am conductor of this omnibus. On 5th May, the prisoners got in at Thomas-street in the Borough—the last witness made a com<lb></lb>munication to me when they got in—in consequence of that I occasionally looked in the omnibus—I recollect the prosecutrix getting in between London-bridge and Gracechurch-street—Jones sat on her right side and Grant sat opposite to her—I was called to to stop, and the prisoners got out on the other side of Cornhill—on their stepping out one of them paid me a shilling for the two, and I gave her change—they both left and went across the road—I received some information from the driver, made some inquiries of the persons in the omnibus, and the prosecutriz said that she had lost something—I went after the prisoners with a policeman—when I came up to them they were in a passage in the street, I gave them into custody and fetched the prosecutrix.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How many persons were in the omnibus when the prisoners got in? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It was pretty full; I cannot tell whether there were ten or twelve—I think Jones sat the fourth or fifth from the door—they had crossed the road before I said anything to anybody inside the omnibus.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-484" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-484" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-484" type="surname" value="TERRY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-484" type="given" value="REBECCA"></interp>REBECCA TERRY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Charles Masters Terry, of Sutton-street, York-road. I got into the omnibus in Gracechurch-street—I do not remember seeing the prisoners—I had my purse in my hand just before I got in, and I believe I put it into my pocket—I intended to do so—the conductor made a remark, and I put my hand into my pocket, and did not find my purse—I do not know what was in it, but I believe there was 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—that was found in it—a gentleman took me to a passage—I there</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140284"></xptr>
               <p>saw these prisoners—one of them said to me, "Here is the purse, don't say we had it"—I took it—they were close together—one heard what the other said—as far as I remember she said, "Here is the purse, don't say we had it"—I did not wish to prosecute—I did not look in the purse at the time—I looked at it at the station house, and there was 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in it—the officer said something to me—I do not think the prisoners heard it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RIBTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were there many people about? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I should think there were forty or fifty—I did not say that I had my purse in my hand—I did not say, "Here is my pmrse;" or, "I have got my purse in my hand"—I do not know who put the purse into my hand—I suppose it was the one that spoke to me—I did not say, "Why, here I have got it in my hand"—it was quite my intention to put my purse into my pocket when I got to the omnibus, I will not swear that I did so—I paid the conductor when I got out; I did not take the money out of my purse, I had some halfpence in my pocket—the conductor asked me if I had lost anything—that was before I paid him—I did not intend to get oat—I had but one pocket; that was on my right side.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you gloves on? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I kept them on when the conductor spoke to me—I did not pull my glove off; I put my hand into my pocket with my glove on—I thought from the conductor's question that I had dropped the purse and the conductor had found it—when one of the prisoners said this to me, the policeman was talking to the conductor—I suppose he was three or four yards from me—there were many persons nearer to me than he was—several of the passengers got out before I got out.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. COOPER</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was this an old fashioned pocket? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It was in my dress on my right hand side—the purse was the only thing I received in that passage, that I am quite sure of.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">HENRY DEAN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> On which side of Mrs. Terry did the prisoner who sat by her, sit? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> On the right side.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-485" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-485" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-485" type="surname" value="GOWLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-485" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS GOWLAND</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a silversmith and jeweller, I live in Leaden-hall-street. On the afternoon of 5th May, the two prisoners came hastily into my passage, and I went to the door of my shop—immediately a crowd came round—the lady came up with the policeman—the prisoners were brought further into the passage to the side door of the house—I begged the policeman to keep the people back, and said he had better bring the lady farther in—they went in, and I heard the prisoners urging the lady to take the purse back again—I saw Jones put her hand towards the prosecntrix with something in it—she appeared to me to pass it to the prosecutrix—the prosecutrix said they had given her the purse back again—the prisoners could hear that.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RIBTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were you in the shop? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, in the passage, I went from the shop to the passage—I saw something in one of the prisoners' hands—I could not tell exactly what it was—it was about the size of the purse—I saw the left hand closed and something in it—I understood from what was said, that they were urging her to take it back—I immediately told the policeman—I cannot tell positively what was said, but I concluded they were urging her to take it back, by their words and actions—before forming that conclusion, I heard the evidence before the Magistrate—there were a few persons outside, I got the policeman to keep them back from the passage—it is the passage leading to my side door—my window goes up the passage, it forms a lobby to my shop.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-486" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-486" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-486" type="surname" value="JACOB"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-486" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN JACOB</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">City policeman</hi>, 35). On 5th May, about 6 o'clock in the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140285"></xptr>
               <p>evening, the conductor came to me and I followed die prisoners to the passage of No. 5, Leadenhall-street—I said, "The conductor says there has Seen a lady robbed in the omnibus, and you are suspected of being the parties"—they said, "It is not us, we will go and see the lady"—I said, "Do you live here?"—they said, "No, we are going to make a call"—I did not let them go—I said, "You must remain here till the lady comes"—just then the lady came up—I asked if she had been robbed—she said, "Yes"—I asked if she knew the parties—she said, "No"—Grant came to the outside of the passage endeavouring to get out, and Jones was with the proeecutrix farther in the passage, and Jones turned round and said, "The lady has found her purse, she is not going to press the charge against us"—I said to the lady, "Is that true?"—she held the purse up, but made no answer—I then took them to the station, and in going Jones said she hoped I should not say anything against her, and she would well recom<lb></lb>pense me for it; and Grant threw down or let fall three sovereigns and a Half sovereign—Jones said, "You will go to my address, won't you?"—I said, "I shall go to the one you give me"—she said, "I hope, you will do something for me, a half sovereign would go a long way"—I said, "It is no talking, to me in that way, all you say I shall say before the Magis<lb></lb>trate"—she said, "Then all I said will die away"—I went to the address she gave, No. 24, Walworth-road.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RIBTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you see the prosecutrix come up? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I was not near enough to hear all that passed between her and Jones, for Grant came to me and was wanting to get out—Jones and the prosecutrix were at the end of the passage, I could see them, but could not see their movements—I might be two yards from them when Jones dropped? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I turned round just as they were dropped, one of them was rolling towards me—I stooped and picked it up, and another person took up the others—Grant did not show a hole in her pocket before me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-487" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-487" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-487" type="surname" value="FITZGERALD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-487" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM FITZGERALD</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">City policeman</hi>, 536). I was with the last witness conveying the prisoners to the station—I saw three sovereigns and a half drop from Grant—I picked up a half sovereign, and three sovereigns were picked up in my presence.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">JONES</hi>*—<hi rend="smallCaps">
